question.text: All of the following are true statements regarding molality EXCEPT one. Which one is the EXCEPTION?

options.label: A.
options.text: The SI unit for molality is mol•kg -1

options.label: B.
options.text: Molality does not depend on the volume of the solvent

options.label: D.
options.text: Molality does not change with pressure

options.label: E.
options.text: Both molality and molarity change with temperature

correct_answer_text: Both molality and molarity change with temperature

explanation.concept_text: Keep in mind that we need to identify the statement that is false regarding molality. Option A. The SI unit for molality is mol• kg -1 Incorrect. Mol·kg -1 is the correct unit for molality. Option B. Molality does not depend on the volume of the solvent Incorrect. Molality depends on the moles of solute and the kg of solvent, NOT the volume. Option C. Molality is an intensive property Incorrect. Intensive properties depend only on the type of matter and not the amount. Molality is an intensive property as it is unaffected by the quantity of the substance. To illustrate this point, if we were to compare a small sample and a large sample of the same solution, both would exhibit the same molality. Extensive properties, in contrast, change depending on the quantity of the substance. Option D. Molality does not change with pressure Incorrect. Molality is independent of pressure changes. Option E. Both molality and molarity change with temperature Correct. A change in temperature will ultimately increase or decrease the volume of the solvent (e.g., solution volume increases with temperature through expansion), thus changing the molarity. On the other hand, as temperature does not affect the mass (kg) of solvent, molality remains unaffected. Therefore, molality does NOT change with temperature while molarity does . Therefore, the answer is E .
